District_Attorney: {
	Name: Defiled Amalgamation
	Text:
		'''
		"That creature... it seems so... distraught?"

		"I mean, if you had the collective consciousness of every being warped to the Defiled, wouldn't you be so hostile?"

		"I wouldn't say *every* being. The Defiled is still quite small compared to the other three evils out there."

		"The Amalgamation is the oldest known being in the Defiled's possession, it has went through so many chunks that I hardly doubt it even has one memory of itself."


		Overview:
			- The Defiled Amalgamation is the oldest known entity in the Defiled's hold as evident with its uniquely large size. The creature is known to prevent intruders from reaching the caverns of the Defiled Wastelands.

		Characteristics:
			- The Amalgamation adopts the same desaturated, misfigured appearance like any other Defiled creature, however, its size is surely a unique characteristic that not many other anti-bodies can share. It also bears a prominent avian physiology, moreso than Defiled Phantoms. Behaviorally, the Amalgamation is very volatile and sporadic. It also can be quite territorial and regularly guards the entrances to the Defiled Caverns on the surface.
							
		Origins:
			- The Defiled Amalgamation's original form is not known, but it could likely be assumed that it was once a bird based on its physiology. Aside from that, it went through a the same process like any other creature being assimilated to the Defiled will that being "refactoring defiledization”.

		Speculation:
			- It is known that the Defiled Amalgamation contains the memories of many different beings assimilated to the Defiled. It could likely be assumed that the Amalgamation is seen as a higher entity than the other creatures that wander the wastes, but a heirarchy has not been confirmed to be present.
		'''
}

Lost_Ore: {
	Name: Lost Ore
	Text:
		'''
		Lost Ore (title)
		[i:Origins/Lost_Ore_Item] [i:Origins/Defiled_Bar] (enlarge to span top of page)

		Overview: 
			- Lost Ore is the primary metal material used by the Defiled entity to create the compound known as "Defiled Matter". Lost Ore is not a material directly tied in with the Defiled, and thus is impossible to be assimilated from. It is quite a versatile material, but cannot be utilized like many other metal materials available due to its mysterious properties.
							
		Characteristics: 
			- Lost Ore, being derived from Iron Ore [i:Terraria/Iron_Ore_Item], shares little in common. Lost Ore is certainly lighter, more reflective, less dense, and significantly less conductive. It takes on a bright white coloration and is also very magnetic to allow for easy movement by the Defiled's means.
							
		Origins: 
			- Lost Ore occurs commonly in the Defiled Caverns and elsewhere in the world where the Defiled plans to propagate. In this case, Lost Ore serves as a catalyst to the Defiled's spread across the world. It additionally likes to keep Lost Ore in numerous reserves underground in hopes that they will not be tampered with. By extracting Lost Ore, an individual could slow the spread of the Defiled.
							
		Chemistry:
			- Lost Ore's primary use is to serve as a readily available metal material to integrate into newly generated Defiled Matter. It is responsible for giving Defiled Matter its smooth, metallic appearance, which is a sign of the Matter's toughness. Lost Ore can alternatively be used as refined material, but the means of refining it are unknown as is its appearance. The main way to utilize Lost Ore's capabilities is to combine it with a live Defiled host, i. e. Undead Chunks [i:Origins/Undead_Chunk].
							
		History: 
			- Lost Ore wasn't always available to the Defiled, at least not initially. The Defiled had to spread enough to reach the caverns of Terraria in order to discover the natural ore that resides there. After discovering a particular vein of Iron Ore [i:Terraria/Iron_Ore_Item], it absorbed it and integrated it into its current production of Defiled Matter. However, the entity found that Iron was too heavy and too conductive for its liking and thus reconfigured Iron's characteristics to be more favorable; the result was Lost Ore.
		'''
}

